<section class="hero">
    <h1><em>Bitcoin-Backed</em> Mortgages</h1>
    <div class="hero-subtitle">Pledge, don&rsquo;t sell &mdash; what the Fannie-Mae-conforming product actually is, why it has no margin call, and when it makes sense for bitcoiners holding an appreciated stack.</div>
    <p class="subtitle">For most of the last decade, bitcoiners faced a binary decision when it came to buying a house: sell BTC for the down payment, or stay out of the housing market entirely. The 2025&ndash;26 Fannie-Mae-conforming product co-built by Coinbase, Better Home &amp; Finance, and the Government-Sponsored Enterprise (GSE) itself is the first regulated US offering to break that binary choice &mdash; and it&rsquo;s structurally different from the CeFi bitcoin-backed loans that defined the prior decade in ways that matter.</p>
</section>

<main class="content-area">
    {% include 'components/tool-framing.njk' %}

    <article class="bbm-page">

        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 1: The pledge instead of the sale                        -->
        <!-- The opening framing. Why this product exists, what it solves.   -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-intro">
                <h2>The pledge instead of the sale</h2>
                <p>According to industry data cited by the issuing parties, roughly <strong>41% of American families with the income to qualify for a conforming mortgage can&rsquo;t close on one for lack of liquid cash for the down payment</strong> &mdash; even when their balance sheet includes substantial non-traditional wealth. For a bitcoin holder, the challenge is felt as more significant because most bitcoiners foresee bitcoin gaining in value far more than real estate, and are loath to reduce their stack.</p>
            </div>

            <p class="prose">The structural argument on <a href="/borrowing-against-your-stack.html"><em>Borrowing Against Your Stack</em></a> applies in full here: if you believe bitcoin&rsquo;s long-run trajectory continues to produce a compound annual growth rate meaningfully higher than your cost of debt, every coin sold today is a coin that compounds for someone else, instead of for you. For the housing transaction specifically, the conceptual argument to borrow against your bitcoin rather than sell for the down payment has held up for years, but has been practically blocked by the lack of a regulated product that lets a bitcoiner pledge the stack instead of selling it. The Fannie-Mae-conforming offering closes that gap.</p>

            <p class="prose">The category is currently bitcoin-only at the GSE level. Bitcoin-backed mortgages have existed for years through private offerings (Milo, the original Bitcoin-backed origination platform, was the most prominent), but the Coinbase / Better Home / Fannie Mae product is the first to bring bitcoin pledging inside the conforming-loan envelope &mdash; with all the institutional infrastructure that implies. <em>That regulators landed on bitcoin specifically, rather than &ldquo;crypto&rdquo; broadly, is itself a meaningful signal about where the regulated tier has come down on collateral quality.</em></p>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 2: Anatomy of the product                                -->
        <!-- The mechanical description. Who plays what role.                -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>Anatomy of the product</h3>
            <p class="prose">The transaction is a <strong>two-loan structure</strong>, not a single bitcoin-backed mortgage. The primary mortgage is a standard 30-year conforming loan against the property &mdash; everything traditional about a mortgage applies to that piece. Riding alongside it is a <em>second-lien down-payment loan</em> collateralized by pledged bitcoin (or USDC) held with a regulated custodian. The pair operates together: the second-lien funds the down payment so the borrower doesn&rsquo;t have to sell BTC; the primary mortgage covers the rest in the conventional way.</p>

            <p class="prose">The second-lien is a normal amortizing loan, not a balloon facility &mdash; <strong>monthly payments on the second-lien include both interest and principal, just like any second mortgage, and the principal pays down to zero over the loan&rsquo;s term.</strong> The pledged bitcoin is the security that protects the lender if you default; it is never the repayment vehicle under normal operation. As long as you make the monthly payments, your bitcoin sits in custody untouched for the full life of the loan.</p>

            <div class="bbm-roles">
                <div class="bbm-role">
                    <div class="bbm-role-name">Fannie Mae</div>
                    <p>Sets conforming standards. The GSE wrapper is what makes this product fundamentally different from the prior decade of CeFi BTC-backed lending &mdash; it brings federal oversight, securitization-grade underwriting, and the standard mortgage-servicing infrastructure to a product whose collateral is digital.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-role">
                    <div class="bbm-role-name">Better Home &amp; Finance</div>
                    <p>Originates and services the loan. The mortgage-industry counterparty providing the underwriting, payment processing, escrow, and servicing rails. Closing-day experience is mostly indistinguishable from a conventional mortgage from the borrower&rsquo;s side.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-role">
                    <div class="bbm-role-name">Coinbase</div>
                    <p>Holds the pledged collateral as the regulated custodian. The bitcoin (or USDC) sits in segregated accounts under the same custody framework that institutional holders use &mdash; not commingled, not rehypothecated, not lent out to third parties. PPSI-designated stablecoins under the GENIUS Act qualify; non-PPSI stablecoins don&rsquo;t.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p class="prose">The economics of the bitcoin-backed second-lien typically run <strong>0.5 to 1.5 percentage points</strong> above the standard 30-year mortgage rate. That spread is the cost of the regulated custody, the specialized monitoring, and the absence of rehypothecation revenue that subsidizes rates on CeFi BTC loans. It&rsquo;s a meaningful number to model against your alternatives &mdash; especially the alternative of selling for the down payment, where the &ldquo;cost&rdquo; is the forgone future appreciation (opportunity cost) of the BTC sold rather than an ongoing fiat interest rate burden.</p>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 3: The structural difference — no margin call            -->
        <!-- The single most important structural feature. Why CeFi BTC      -->
        <!-- loans aren't the precedent reader expects.                       -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>The structural difference: no margin call</h3>
            <p class="prose"><em>This is the feature that separates the Fannie-Mae-conforming product from every CeFi bitcoin-backed loan that came before it.</em> Traditional CeFi BTC lending uses an LTV trigger &mdash; a market-driven liquidation threshold that forces sale of collateral the moment bitcoin&rsquo;s price puts the LTV above some pre-set band (typically 75&ndash;90%). In a meaningful drawdown, a healthy borrower paying interest on time can still have their position closed by the market.</p>

            <p class="prose">The mortgage product structurally eliminates this. Market movements alone do not trigger liquidation of the pledged collateral. Risk management is aligned with the standard real-estate delinquency timeline, not the crypto-LTV one. <em>Here&rsquo;s the full sequence &mdash; three steps that are indistinguishable from any conforming mortgage, and one step that is the actionable threshold. The contrast with the CeFi model is the point: under CeFi, a sufficiently large drawdown anywhere in this window would have already force-liquidated a healthy borrower.</em></p>

            <div class="bbm-sequence">
                <div class="bbm-step">
                    <div class="bbm-step-rank">1</div>
                    <div class="bbm-step-body">
                        <div class="bbm-step-title">Missed payment</div>
                        <p>You miss a scheduled monthly mortgage payment. Nothing happens to the pledged collateral.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-step">
                    <div class="bbm-step-rank">2</div>
                    <div class="bbm-step-body">
                        <div class="bbm-step-title">Notification &amp; grace period</div>
                        <p>The servicer reaches out for standard late-payment resolution &mdash; exactly as on any conforming loan. Bitcoin price during this window is irrelevant.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-step">
                    <div class="bbm-step-rank">3</div>
                    <div class="bbm-step-body">
                        <div class="bbm-step-title">Delinquency (Days 1&ndash;59)</div>
                        <p>The loan is marked delinquent. <em>The pledged collateral remains untouched regardless of bitcoin&rsquo;s price movements.</em> A 50% drawdown during this window changes nothing about your collateral.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-step bbm-step-action">
                    <div class="bbm-step-rank">4</div>
                    <div class="bbm-step-body">
                        <div class="bbm-step-title">Actionable default (Day 60+)</div>
                        <p>Only after the borrower is at least 60 days delinquent &mdash; the same threshold that initiates the foreclosure process on any conforming mortgage &mdash; does the collateral become subject to liquidation to cover the debt.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p class="prose">The implication is large for any bitcoiner who has internalized the <em>Loan Health</em> framework on the <a href="/borrowing-against-your-stack.html#loan-health">borrowing page</a>: the liquidation-price math that dominates the CeFi case largely doesn&rsquo;t apply here. <strong>Your liquidation risk is now driven by your ability to make monthly mortgage payments, not by bitcoin&rsquo;s drawdown profile.</strong> The Power Law channel still matters &mdash; but as the long-duration thesis behind why the pledge is worth making, not as the timing dial for liquidation survival.</p>

            <div class="narrative" style="margin-top:1.5rem;margin-bottom:2rem;padding:1.75rem 2.25rem;border-left-width:3px">
                <p style="font-family:'Cormorant Garamond',serif;font-size:1.1rem;line-height:1.6;color:var(--text);font-style:italic">The structural failure mode of the prior decade of bitcoin-backed lending &mdash; force-liquidation of healthy borrowers by routine market volatility &mdash; is absent here by design. That doesn&rsquo;t make this product universally appropriate. It does make it categorically different from the CeFi loans that defined the prior history.</p>
            </div>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 4: The three pledge advantages                           -->
        <!-- The fiscal/operational benefits of pledging vs selling.         -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>Three advantages of pledging instead of selling</h3>
            <p class="prose">The fiscal mechanics behind why a bitcoiner would prefer this product to selling for a down payment break down into three distinct benefits.</p>

            <div class="bbm-advantages">
                <div class="bbm-advantage">
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-num">01</div>
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-title">Stack integrity</div>
                    <p>Your stack is preserved. Selling 1 BTC at today&rsquo;s price to fund a down payment trades that 1 BTC&rsquo;s entire future trajectory &mdash; including the long-duration Power Law trend &mdash; for the immediate fiat amount. Pledging it instead keeps that coin in your stack, compounding for you, while still funding the down payment.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-advantage">
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-num">02</div>
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-title">Tax deferral</div>
                    <p>Selling triggers a capital-gains event &mdash; up to 20% federal LTCG plus any state tax. Pledging is a loan against the asset, not a disposition, and so the tax liability stays attached to the asset at its original basis. The gain only realizes if and when you actually sell.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bbm-advantage">
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-num">03</div>
                    <div class="bbm-advantage-title">Yield offsetting</div>
                    <p>If the collateral pledged is a PPSI-designated stablecoin (USDC under the GENIUS Act) rather than bitcoin, the holder can in many configurations continue to earn yield on the pledged balance &mdash; partially offsetting the mortgage interest. The economics there depend on platform-specific terms.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 5: The compliance reality                                -->
        <!-- The tax tracing rules, the deduction limits.                    -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>The compliance reality</h3>
            <p class="prose">Three regulatory features the borrower has to navigate concretely:</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>The &sect;1259 design.</strong> Section 1259 of the IRS code &mdash; the &ldquo;constructive sale&rdquo; doctrine that the 2026 PARITY Act explicitly extended to digital assets &mdash; deems an asset sold for tax purposes if its owner enters offsetting positions that substantially eliminate price risk and gain. The Coinbase / Better Home / Fannie Mae structure is <em>specifically</em> designed to avoid triggering this: no mandatory price-based hedges, no market-driven liquidations, no margin call. The borrower retains full price exposure on the pledged collateral, which is precisely what keeps the pledge a loan rather than a deemed sale. <em>This is structural intent on the part of the product&rsquo;s designers, not coincidence.</em></p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>Loan tracing for interest deductibility.</strong> IRS rules require that proceeds of a loan be traced to their use to determine whether the interest is deductible. Mortgage interest on the primary mortgage is deductible under the standard home-acquisition rules (subject to the 2026 cap on itemized deductions at 35% for top earners). The second-lien down-payment loan also generally qualifies as acquisition debt if the proceeds are documented as funding the down payment specifically. <em>The documentation burden falls on the borrower &mdash; maintain separate accounts, signed loan agreements, and quarterly custodian statements so the audit trail is clean if the IRS ever asks.</em></p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>The standard-deduction trade-off.</strong> The mortgage-interest deduction is real but generic to any mortgage product and often smaller than marketing implies once the 2026 standard deduction ($16,100 single / $32,200 joint) is netted against itemized interest. Model it explicitly against your bracket and likely loan size before counting on it &mdash; it&rsquo;s not bitcoin-specific.</p>

            <div class="bbm-checklist">
                <div class="bbm-checklist-label">Compliance checklist</div>
                <p class="bbm-checklist-framing"><em>The compliance overhead is real but routine. Most of this paperwork is generated automatically by the servicer and the custodian as part of the normal product operation &mdash; the borrower&rsquo;s job is largely to keep it filed and accessible if the IRS ever asks. The bitcoin-collateral piece doesn&rsquo;t meaningfully increase the work beyond what a conventional second-mortgage borrower already does.</em></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Dedicated bank account for the second-lien proceeds and the down payment disbursement &mdash; makes IRS tracing trivial</li>
                    <li>Signed copies of <em>both</em> loan agreements (primary mortgage and second-lien) retained for the life of the loans</li>
                    <li>Quarterly custodian statements from Coinbase confirming the status and amount of pledged collateral</li>
                    <li>Form 1098 (or equivalent) interest summaries from the servicer at year-end for each loan</li>
                    <li>Annual reconciliation between the pledged collateral statement and the LTV ratio implied by the loan balance and market value</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>


        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <!-- SECTION 6: When this makes sense — and when it doesn't           -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>When this makes sense &mdash; and when it doesn&rsquo;t</h3>

            <p class="prose"><em>This page isn&rsquo;t recommending bitcoin-backed mortgages.</em> Like the parent <a href="/borrowing-against-your-stack.html">Borrowing Against Your Stack</a> page, the editorial mission is structural literacy: walk the reader through what the product is, how it&rsquo;s different from its CeFi predecessors, what risks remain, and what the trade-off actually is &mdash; so you can evaluate it on your own terms.</p>

            <p class="prose">The trade clears the bar when several conditions are met together:</p>

            <ul class="bbm-checklist-good">
                <li>You&rsquo;re buying a <em>primary residence</em>, not a speculative investment property. The product&rsquo;s economics are designed around long-duration owner-occupancy.</li>
                <li>You have the income to service the monthly mortgage payments from your day-job cash flow. The &ldquo;no margin call&rdquo; feature only protects you against price volatility; it doesn&rsquo;t protect you against income loss.</li>
                <li>Your bitcoin stack is large enough that the pledged collateral represents a modest fraction of the total &mdash; ideally well below 50% &mdash; so a Day-60 default scenario doesn&rsquo;t risk forcing liquidation of the bulk of your position.</li>
                <li>You&rsquo;d rather not crystallize the capital-gains liability on the pledged BTC at this stage of your life. The tax deferral compounds across decades for younger holders especially.</li>
                <li>You believe bitcoin&rsquo;s long-run trajectory continues to produce a compound annual growth rate meaningfully higher than the mortgage rate over the duration of the loan. <em>This is the Power Law channel argument; it has to be true for the pledge to be the better path.</em></li>
            </ul>

            <p class="prose">The trade fails the bar when:</p>

            <ul class="bbm-checklist-bad">
                <li>The use case is anything other than primary-residence purchase &mdash; investment property, second home for speculative purposes, vacation home as a discretionary asset</li>
                <li>The mortgage payments stretch your monthly cash flow such that any income disruption puts the entire structure at risk</li>
                <li>You don&rsquo;t actually believe in the long-duration bitcoin appreciation case &mdash; in which case selling some BTC for the down payment is genuinely the cheaper path, since you&rsquo;re not giving up appreciation you don&rsquo;t expect to see</li>
                <li>You&rsquo;d be relying on the mortgage-interest tax deduction to make the economics work &mdash; the deduction is smaller than marketed and the standard-deduction comparison usually narrows it materially</li>
            </ul>
        </div>


